def _label_to_colors(labels):
    map_label_to_color = {
        0: [255, 255, 255],  # white unclassified
        1: [153, 255, 153],  # light green natural ground
        2: [0, 204, 0],  # green low vegetation
        3: [0, 102, 0],  # dark green high vegetation
        4: [102, 0, 0],  # dark red buildings
        5: [0, 76, 153],  # blue road
        6: [6, 96, 96],  # grey wire structure
        7: [255, 69, 0],  # orangered vehicules
        8: [128, 0, 128],  # Purple trash can
        9: [128, 0, 0],  # maron street signs
        10: [160, 82, 45],  #Sienna lamps
        11: [128, 128, 0],  # olive remaining hard scapes
        12: [255, 255, 0],  # yellow wall
        13: [102, 255, 255],  #  light blue manmade terrain
        14: [255, 215, 0],  # gold barrier
        15: [176, 224, 230],  #  PowderBlue cycling_path
    }
    a = np.array([map_label_to_color[label] for label in labels]).astype(np.int32)
    return pd.DataFrame(a,columns=['R', 'G', 'B'])

This new classification has garanteed a relatively significant ious of all classes except for the remaining hardscapes and barrier but it did not improve any of the IOUs for classes that has been trained on the previous classification.Hence, eventhough the elimination of classes that do not show any significant IOU has improved the overall accuracy, it did not enhance the IOU per class and in some classes it got even worse. You can compare this (df) with the previous training when I used the same data and parameters for training and validation including all the 24 classes in the table df1 below

def _label_to_colors(labels):
    map_label_to_color = {
        0: [255, 255, 255],  # white unclassified
        1: [153, 255, 153],  # light green natural ground
        2: [0, 204, 0],  # green low vegetation
        3: [0, 102, 0],  # dark green high vegetation
        4: [102, 0, 0],  # dark red buildings
        5: [0, 76, 153],  # blue road
        6: [6, 96, 96],  # grey wire structure
        7: [255, 69, 0],  # orangered vehicules
        8: [160, 82, 45],  #Sienna lamps
        9: [128, 0, 0],  # maron street signs
        10: [102, 255, 255],  #  light blue manmade terrain
        11: [255, 215, 0],  # gold barrier
    }
    a = np.array([map_label_to_color[label] for label in labels]).astype(np.int32)
    return pd.DataFrame(a,columns=['R', 'G', 'B'])

def _label_to_colors(labels):
    map_label_to_color = {
        0: [255, 255, 255],  # white unclassified
        1: [153, 255, 153],  # light green natural ground
        2: [0, 204, 0],  # green low vegetation
        3: [0, 102, 0],  # dark green high vegetation
        4: [102, 0, 0],  # dark red buildings
        5: [0, 76, 153],  # blue road
        6: [6, 96, 96],  # grey wire structure
        7: [255, 69, 0],  # orangered vehicules
        8: [160, 82, 45],  #Sienna lamps
        9: [128, 0, 0],  # maron street signs
        10: [102, 255, 255],  #  light blue manmade terrain
        11: [255, 215, 0],  # gold barrier
        12: [128, 128, 0],  # remaining hard scapes
    }
    a = np.array([map_label_to_color[label] for label in labels]).astype(np.int32)
    return pd.DataFrame(a,columns=['R', 'G', 'B'])
